The angles of triangle $PQR$ add up to $180^\circ$, so  \[\angle PQR + \angle PRQ + \angle QRP = 180^\circ.\]Substituting $\angle PQR = \angle PRQ$ and $\angle QRP = 65^\circ$, we get \[\angle PRQ + \angle PRQ + 65^\circ = 180^\circ.\]Solving for $\angle PRQ$, we find $\angle PRQ = 57.5^\circ$.  Since $\angle PQS$ and $\angle PRQ$ are supplementary, we have  \[x^\circ + 57.5^\circ = 180^\circ.\]Solving for $x$, we find $x = \boxed{122.5}$.  Final Answer: $\boxed{122.5}$. ground_truth: Since the sum of the angles in any triangle is $180^\circ,$ then looking at $\triangle QSR,$ we have \[ \angle SQR = 180^\circ - \angle QSR - \angle SRQ = 180^\circ - 90^\circ - 65^\circ = 25^\circ \]Since $PQ = PR,$ then $\angle PQR = \angle PRQ.$ Thus, $x^\circ + 25^\circ = 65^\circ$ or $x+25=65$, and so $x = \boxed{40}.$
